Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** for a (fictional) C++ library *libpcapng* that parses a PCAP‑NG file and exposes an iterator over its frames.  
The binding lets OCaml code “do something” for every frame that the iterator yields – exactly what you asked for.

The package consists of two files:

* `pcapng.mli` – the public OCaml interface that users will `open Pcapng`.
* `pcapng_stubs.cpp` – the C‑/C++‑level glue that talks to libpcapng and to the OCaml runtime.

Both files are written so that they can be compiled with the normal OCaml build tools (`ocamlopt`, `ocamlc`, `dune`, …).  
Only a tiny mock of *libpcapng* is included in the stub file – replace the mock with the real header(s) when you ship the real library.

---

## 1.  The OCaml interface (`pcapng.mli`)

```ocaml
(** {1 PCAP‑NG bindings} *)

(** A handle to an opened PCAP‑NG file.  The value is opaque – it is
    allocated by [open_file] and must be released with [close]. *)
type t

(** A single captured frame.  The type is deliberately kept small; a
    richer view can be added later if needed. *)
type frame = {
  data      : bytes;      (** Raw packet bytes *)
  timestamp : int64;     (** Timestamp in nanoseconds since the epoch *)
}

(** {2 Basic operations} *)

(** Open a PCAP‑NG file for reading.  Raises [Invalid_argument] if the
    file cannot be opened or is not a valid PCAP‑NG file. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Close a previously opened file.  After this call the handle must
    not be used again.  It is safe to call [close] more than once. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** {2 Iteration primitives} *)

(** Iterate over all frames in the file, calling the supplied OCaml
    function for each frame.  The callback is allowed to raise; the
    iteration stops immediately and the exception propagates to the
    caller.  The iteration is performed on the C++ side, so the
    callback is invoked *C‑to‑OCaml* for every frame – no intermediate
    OCaml list is built. *)
val iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** Fold over the frames.  The implementation is just a thin wrapper
    around [iter] and therefore has the same performance
    characteristics. *)
val fold : t -> ('a -> frame -> 'a) -> 'a -> 'a

(** A more low‑level primitive: fetch the next frame, or [None] if the
    iterator is exhausted.  The function can be called repeatedly until
    it returns [None]; it is equivalent to a manual “while
    has_next() … next()” loop on the C++ side. *)
val next : t -> frame option
```

### How a user would employ the API

```ocaml
open Pcapng

let print_frame f =
  Printf.printf "frame %Ld bytes @ %Ld ns\n%!"
    (Int64.of_int (Bytes.length f.data))
    f.timestamp

let () =
  let h = open_file "sample.pcapng" in
  (* 1️⃣  Simple iteration – every frame is printed *)
  iter h print_frame;

  (* 2️⃣  Fold – count frames with length > 1000 bytes *)
  let big = fold h (fun acc f ->
      if Bytes.length f.data > 1000 then acc + 1 else acc) 0 in
  Printf.printf "There are %d big frames\n%!" big;

  close h
```

