## 3.  How to build the binding

### With `ocamlopt` (stand‑alone)

```bash
# Compile the stub (make sure a C++ compiler is used)
ocamlopt -c -ccopt -std=c++17 pcapng_stubs.cpp

# Compile the interface (no .ml file needed – we expose only the .mli)
ocamlopt -c pcapng.mli

# Build a library (optional)
ocamlopt -a -o libpcapng.cmxa pcapng.cmx pcapng_stubs.o -cclib -lstdc++

# Example program:
cat > test.ml <<'EOF'
open Pcapng

let () =
  let h = open_file Sys.argv.(1) in
  iter h (fun f ->
      Printf.printf "frame %d bytes @ %Ld ns\n%!"
        (Bytes.length f.data) f.timestamp);
  close h
EOF

ocamlopt -o test.exe libpcapng.cmxa test.ml -cclib -lstdc++
```

### With Dune

`dune` makes the boilerplate easier:

```dune
(library
 (name pcapng)
 (public_name pcapng)
 (modules pcapng)
 (libraries stdlib)
 (foreign_stubs
  (language cxx)
  (names pcapng_stubs)))
```

Place `pcapng.mli` and `pcapng_stubs.cpp` in the same directory; Dune will compile the stub as C++ and link everything automatically.

